WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.330 --> 00:00:07.704
BENNY LEWIS: Thank
you very much.

00:00:07.704 --> 00:00:11.496
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.496 --> 00:00:12.750
Hey, everyone.

00:00:12.750 --> 00:00:16.110
I want to talk to you
today about a little bit

00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:17.990
of a life of adventure.

00:00:17.990 --> 00:00:20.480
I have the same background
many of you have.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:22.560
I studied electronic
engineering,

00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:26.500
right here in UC-D.
And I didn't really

00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:28.000
know what that was
going to lead to.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.550
I just found the one
thing that I was good at.

00:00:30.550 --> 00:00:33.920
I was good at maths,
I was good at science,

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:35.810
and I rolled with it.

00:00:35.810 --> 00:00:38.040
And I didn't know where
that would take me.

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:43.370
And what happened was I did
just OK in my final exams.

00:00:43.370 --> 00:00:45.780
And I kind of felt a
little disappointed.

00:00:45.780 --> 00:00:49.740
I didn't want to be
just an OK engineer.

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:54.330
And in the end, my engineering
did come back to help me a lot.

00:00:54.330 --> 00:00:56.230
And I want to talk
about how that ties in

00:00:56.230 --> 00:00:59.160
with this whole
Jason Bourne idea.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.660
So after I finished
my engineering degree,

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:05.690
I started world travels.

00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:10.200
And I had been
homeless for 13 years.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:15.470
Everything I owned had to
weigh less than 23 kilograms,

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:17.150
because that's the weight limit.

00:01:17.150 --> 00:01:20.450
And I would go to places
for three months at a time,

00:01:20.450 --> 00:01:23.270
because that's the
tourist visa limit.

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:25.700
And I would just
keep hopping around.

00:01:25.700 --> 00:01:29.260
And as I did-- come on in.

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:34.200
As I was hopping around, I tried
to learn the local language.

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.050
I know a lot of people
here have the ability

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:38.610
to speak multiple languages.

00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:42.160
You might have done English
as you were growing up,

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:43.660
if you're from another country.

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:47.110
You might have had an experience
living abroad as an intern,

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:49.560
or done an Erasmus here.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:51.600
I didn't have that myself.

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:55.130
I barely passed German
for the leaving cert.

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:58.350
I just got like
a low C. And then

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:02.520
I moved to Spain after
I graduated, lived there

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:06.430
for six months, and I just
spoke English the whole time.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:09.479
But something changed
along the way.

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:11.235
I figured out what
I was doing wrong,

00:02:11.235 --> 00:02:16.150
and I figured out how I
could hack language learning.

00:02:16.150 --> 00:02:17.910
So I'll get to that
in a little bit.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:21.050
But first I want to get
to the kind of stuff

00:02:21.050 --> 00:02:24.330
that I tried to
do with my career

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:28.260
to see how I could find
this job that could really

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:32.510
make a difference, how I could
feel like I am, like, having

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:34.780
an adventure while I'm working.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:37.930
So I've had a lot of
different positions

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:39.690
over the 13 years traveling.

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:41.110
I'm a blogger.

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:44.120
My blog gets a million
unique visitors

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:46.490
per month, very big blog.

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:49.380
I don't have any background
in English-- writing English,

00:02:49.380 --> 00:02:50.350
I should say.

00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:52.170
And I manage to do that.

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:53.870
Professional speaker, like now.

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:57.580
If I hold it in the
same hand, like this.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:59.770
Yeah.

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:01.870
Of course, written a few books.

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:04.480
I wrote these four books over
the last year, had another book

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:05.980
before that.

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:08.620
I was a professional translator.

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:13.010
This is the first time that I
managed to have a lot of fun

00:03:13.010 --> 00:03:15.970
with engineering,
because for many years,

00:03:15.970 --> 00:03:18.580
I didn't really know what to
do with my engineering degree.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:21.750
I thought maybe, you know,
it was fun, I studied it,

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:24.910
but it's not going to
tie in with something

00:03:24.910 --> 00:03:26.114
else I might want to do.

00:03:26.114 --> 00:03:27.530
But after I learned
the languages,

00:03:27.530 --> 00:03:30.410
and I did some certificates
in the languages,

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:34.170
it turned out I was in a
unique position, because there

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:38.600
are very few English-speaking
engineers who

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:40.040
speak other languages.

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.630
It's one reason why they're
so sought after in Google.

00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:43.130
You know?

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:45.330
Obviously, you're going
to bump into a lot

00:03:45.330 --> 00:03:47.310
of multilingual engineers
in this building.

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:50.300
It's not going to happen, as
likely, in other buildings.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:54.400
So I took that,
and I translated.

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:59.560
I translated technical
documents from French, Spanish,

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:01.620
and Italian to English.

00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:04.270
And that was the
first job that let

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:10.560
me travel the world as a
location-independent worker.

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:12.350
I've also been a consultant.

00:04:12.350 --> 00:04:13.650
Those are all recent jobs.

00:04:13.650 --> 00:04:18.000
But like I said, I've had
many, many, many jobs.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.790
I was a youth
hostel receptionist.

00:04:21.790 --> 00:04:24.060
I was an English teacher,
because you end up

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:25.640
doing that a lot
while you travel.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:30.160
I was a maths teacher,
ended up using that.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:31.950
Worked for Johns
Hopkins University.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:36.190
This was for what we
lovingly call "nerd camp."

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:38.570
Happiest place on earth.

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:39.410
You know?

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:40.660
I loved it.

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:45.470
I got to put some energy into
teaching them about Pythagoras.

00:04:45.470 --> 00:04:49.400
I was, like, you know,
saying, "In a world where

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:53.026
this cult of people who
worshipped triangles,"

00:04:53.026 --> 00:04:53.650
and it's great.

00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:55.560
It's the kind of
place you can do that.

00:04:55.560 --> 00:04:58.910
So I used a lot of
that in my travels.

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:01.260
I got to teach maths.

00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:04.250
I got to use
engineering principles.

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:08.360
And of course, I actually
worked as an engineer.

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:12.690
I worked in Paris at a--
this is my gorgeous desk

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:15.130
with the chaotic
mess all over it,

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:19.480
where I was translating
software and working

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:21.830
as a pre-sales engineer.

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:23.612
OK.

00:05:23.612 --> 00:05:24.570
But I'm still not done.

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:26.770
There's so many
other jobs I've had.

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:30.520
My first job, when I was
12, was a FTSE 100 investor,

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:32.490
because I was the
only guy in my town

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.440
who knew how to use a computer.

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:37.739
And someone just wanted to,
like, invest in the FTSE 100,

00:05:37.739 --> 00:05:39.530
and he didn't know how
to use the software.

00:05:39.530 --> 00:05:41.020
So I stepped up to it.

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:43.650
And I was tech support at
the local computer store.

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:45.170
I had a lot of office jobs.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:46.580
This thing here?

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:50.770
That is a laryngeal mask array,
that you put on your larynx

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:51.930
after surgery.

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:55.260
And the only reason I know
that is because I arranged

00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:57.150
the world's literature
on laryngeal mask

00:05:57.150 --> 00:05:59.240
arrays alphabetically
and chronologically

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:01.840
over two months.

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:03.360
Yes.

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:06.310
Very, very not fun, that job.

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:08.510
I was a race car controller.

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:10.470
Not in the Mario world.

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:14.330
I wasn't in that universe
of Super Nintendo.

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:17.280
But I was someone
controlling the race cars,

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:19.770
because I used my
engineering background

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:24.650
to kind of explain that I
could use the equipment better.

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:28.900
And then, nothing to do with
engineering, I ran a yoga shop.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:30.570
The only reason
I got that job is

00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:32.250
because it was in
California, and they

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:35.020
found my Irish accent charming.

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:36.570
They found it soothing.

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:39.030
So I didn't even know-- it was
like, a pregnant lady might

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:41.499
come in and say, which
yoga mat is better for me,

00:06:41.499 --> 00:06:42.290
as a pregnant lady?

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:44.980
And I'd be, like, uh,
well, ah, you know,

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:49.377
as an Irish lad, I would
say, this mat has good zen.

00:06:49.377 --> 00:06:51.210
Not really knowing what
I was talking about.

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:52.810
And it worked.

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:54.600
I was a first aid assistant.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:56.510
Do a quick first
aid course and you

00:06:56.510 --> 00:07:00.574
can work in, like, these camps,
like the one I was working at.

00:07:00.574 --> 00:07:01.990
And I could actually
help the kids

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:05.100
when they ran into
medical problems.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.920
OK, so that's kind of just an
overview of the kind of work

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:09.520
that I've had.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:11.690
I've met people
who have used a lot

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:16.370
of their technical abilities
to really get-- like, get out

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:18.720
there and travel
the world with it.

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:23.060
You could do, like, web
development and coding.

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:24.650
And you could be
an online coach.

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:26.000
You can write, like I've done.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.320
Met people who earn a
living playing poker,

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:32.150
you know, just on these
online forums and stuff.

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:35.440
And there's loads of other
location-independent jobs.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:39.120
But the big question I always
get is, when you're traveling,

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:40.820
is how you can afford it.

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:43.910
So all those jobs I
mentioned, I didn't

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:48.130
have those lined up for me
when I arrived somewhere.

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:53.690
I had to actually figure
out how to spend less money.

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:58.060
So, in the whole kind of Jason
Bourne theme, this behind me

00:07:58.060 --> 00:08:00.430
is Palolem Beach.

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:04.185
That's the beach that
Jason Bourne was living in,

00:08:04.185 --> 00:08:05.570
in the second movie.

00:08:05.570 --> 00:08:08.209
It was shot there the same
summer that I was living there.

00:08:08.209 --> 00:08:09.250
I didn't even realize it.

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:12.360
This is back when
it was being shot.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:16.070
And I was-- like,
I was kind of, see,

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:18.510
I kind of have this
Jason Bourne lifestyle.

00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:21.960
And I have three passports.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:23.980
I managed to hack that one, too.

00:08:23.980 --> 00:08:26.140
And this beach?

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:27.260
Never ran into him.

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:28.230
Wish I did.

00:08:28.230 --> 00:08:34.590
But this hut here, on
this beach in India,

00:08:34.590 --> 00:08:39.679
I got it for about
four euro a night.

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:44.020
And the thing that got it
for me was learning how

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:46.830
to integrate with the culture.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:51.240
This, for me, is like the
feeling of being a spy,

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:57.450
is I got to try to see
how well I can blend in.

00:08:57.450 --> 00:09:01.390
So I traveled India with
an Indian friend of mine.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:05.430
And he owed me a lot
of favors, because I

00:09:05.430 --> 00:09:08.090
was very active in couchsurfing,
if you guys have ever

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:09.240
heard of that website.

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:13.370
I've hosted over
2,000 couchsurfers.

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:18.010
I used couchsurfing as a means
to practice languages for free,

00:09:18.010 --> 00:09:20.560
because as I would be living
somewhere for three months,

00:09:20.560 --> 00:09:23.270
since I had all
of those jobs, I'd

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:27.610
be able to afford to get
an OK apartment to myself.

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:30.420
But I found that when I
did that, I wasn't actually

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:32.290
interacting with
a lot of people,

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:37.330
whereas before, when I would
be-- I would have flatmates,

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:40.830
I would be using them
as my circle of friends.

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:44.621
Well, with couchsurfing, I would
just welcome people to my home.

00:09:44.621 --> 00:09:46.620
And I would try to practice
languages with them,

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:48.270
or get to know their culture.

00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:53.820
And one time in Brazil, I hosted
55 people at the same time,

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.280
during the Carnival,
for a whole week.

00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:00.090
Very, very long queues for
the bathroom that week.

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:03.100
And that-- those 55
people, one of them

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:05.940
included Rahul,
my Indian friend.

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:08.550
So years later, when
I met him in India,

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:11.716
I said, I really want to
get to know the country.

00:10:11.716 --> 00:10:14.340
And he said, I'm not just going
to show you the country, Benny.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:18.030
I'm going to show you how
to think like an Indian.

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:22.140
So a place like this, if
you were to walk up to it

00:10:22.140 --> 00:10:26.570
and have a white face, they
would say 20 euro a night,

00:10:26.570 --> 00:10:29.760
which actually seems like
a pretty good price, when

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:32.710
you compare it to what we
would be used to paying.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:34.590
But my friend, he
said, no, no, no, no.

00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:36.850
That's not how it
works in India.

00:10:36.850 --> 00:10:38.030
You've got to haggle.

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:39.050
And I say, oh, haggle.

00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:39.550
OK.

00:10:39.550 --> 00:10:43.000
So if they say 20, I say 10,
and we meet in the middle.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.200
And he's like, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.650
That's not how it works.

00:10:48.650 --> 00:10:50.401
The way it works, if
you're ever in India,

00:10:50.401 --> 00:10:52.650
and you want to haggle a
price-- and this has actually

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:54.180
worked for me around the world.

00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:56.560
It's a very good
psychological technique.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:59.720
You never mention
the price yourself.

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:02.420
You just mention the
reasons it should go down.

00:11:02.420 --> 00:11:04.730
So I walked up to this place.

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:07.760
The lady was ready
to share it with us.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:09.360
And I said, oh,
how much is this?

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:13.470
And she said, the equivalent
in rupees of about 20 euro.

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:15.614
And I was like, 20 euro?

00:11:15.614 --> 00:11:16.280
No, no, it's OK.

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:18.960
And I started walking away,
like, just disappointed.

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:20.650
And then she said,
OK, OK, OK, OK.

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:22.210
15 euro.

00:11:22.210 --> 00:11:28.430
And I looked over my shoulder,
and I was like, I don't know.

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:30.132
It's, like, right on the beach.

00:11:30.132 --> 00:11:31.590
How am I supposed
to sleep at night

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.070
with all the waves crashing?

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:34.690
You know?

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:36.552
I don't think so.

00:11:36.552 --> 00:11:37.260
I don't think so.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:38.360
And I started
walking away again.

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:39.200
And she said, OK, OK.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:39.720
10 euro.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:40.700
10 euro.

00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:44.500
And still I wasn't
looking at her and, like,

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:47.340
warmly showing, yeah, yeah, I'm
definitely going to get this.

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:51.260
You've got to be
obnoxiously uninterested.

00:11:51.260 --> 00:11:53.300
So it's, like, looking
over my shoulder

00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:57.490
like the place was, like,
smelling bad-- looking at it,

00:11:57.490 --> 00:12:02.100
thinking, but isn't
it facing the sun?

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:04.230
How am I supposed to read
a book on this balcony

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:06.430
with the sun in my eyes?

00:12:06.430 --> 00:12:08.700
And she's like, ugh, OK, fine.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:10.710
And keep in mind,
this is the sun

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:13.610
setting over a beautiful
landscape, you know,

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:17.670
with a gorgeous, like, view
of an island and everything.

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:19.290
But I reframed it.

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:20.980
And I kept giving
more and more reasons.

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:23.340
I was like, yeah, how's the AC?

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:24.940
Does it have, like,
various settings?

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:26.934
And she was like,
there's just a fun.

00:12:26.934 --> 00:12:27.850
It's like, just a fan?

00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:29.980
OK, no way.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:32.390
And then eventually I got
it down to the three or four

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:33.860
euro that it was.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:36.670
So a lot of what
I've tried to do

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:39.950
to get the price
of everything lower

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:43.590
is to try to understand
the local culture,

00:12:43.590 --> 00:12:45.650
try to integrate better.

00:12:45.650 --> 00:12:48.260
And this has given me
that Jason Bourne sense

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.850
of being a spy, that
I'm almost going

00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:53.100
to be mistaken for a local.

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:54.840
It's not going to
happen in India,

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:58.690
but what my goal has been in
countries like India and China,

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:01.330
is be mistaken for
somebody who's lived there

00:13:01.330 --> 00:13:03.170
for a very long time.

00:13:03.170 --> 00:13:06.590
And then they're less likely
to take advantage of you.

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:11.160
So in Egypt, for instance, I
wanted to get better prices.

00:13:11.160 --> 00:13:14.210
So the first thing I did was
try to learn a little bit

00:13:14.210 --> 00:13:16.500
of Egyptian Arabic in advance.

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:20.210
And whenever people think
about learning a language,

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:24.500
they think the best thing to
do is to go to the location.

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:26.730
Fly to the country.

00:13:26.730 --> 00:13:29.015
And I didn't find this
worked for me, because

00:13:29.015 --> 00:13:32.160
in-- when I got to Spain
first, I got off the plane,

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:35.800
and I just imagined, in my
head, I'm in the country.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.590
So I'm just going to
automatically learn

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:38.710
the language.

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:45.380
I'm going to inhale Spanish
air and exhale espanol.

00:13:45.380 --> 00:13:47.862
But that didn't happen,
because I gravitated

00:13:47.862 --> 00:13:49.070
towards the English speakers.

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:53.660
So I've skipped all of that,
and what I do now, that I feel

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:59.140
is a lot more useful, is
I learn via the internet.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:03.410
I find someone and Google
Hangout, or I Skype them,

00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:05.810
or I text them, WhatsApp,
or whatever I can do.

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:09.320
And I get in touch, and
we practice that way.

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:12.540
I have a certain
virtual immersion.

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:14.890
This, for me, has
been a game changer,

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:17.850
because it means I put the time
into learning the language.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:20.387
But then when I get to the
country, I'm not in language

00:14:20.387 --> 00:14:20.970
learning mode.

00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:24.510
I'm in culture learning mode.

00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:27.520
So in Egypt, for instance,
when I first arrived,

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.010
I had some basic
Egyptian Arabic, enough

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:31.860
to get some conversations.

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:34.320
And they still spoke
back to me in English.

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:35.904
And I was like,
ugh, I don't get it.

00:14:35.904 --> 00:14:36.570
What's going on?

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:38.020
I put all this work in.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.570
But then I tried
something different.

00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:41.640
I sat down in a
cafe, pen and paper,

00:14:41.640 --> 00:14:45.800
and I started making notes of
how Egyptian men around my age

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:47.220
were different to me.

00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:50.410
And maybe I wasn't
showing the culture enough

00:14:50.410 --> 00:14:52.930
of a-- enough respect.

00:14:52.930 --> 00:14:54.770
I wasn't trying to integrate.

00:14:54.770 --> 00:14:56.630
And I actually noticed
a lot of things.

00:14:56.630 --> 00:15:00.030
I noticed that they groom
themselves differently.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:03.097
I needed to grow
out, like, a beard.

00:15:03.097 --> 00:15:04.180
Didn't do a very good job.

00:15:04.180 --> 00:15:06.270
My Facebook friends
called it a porn 'tache.

00:15:06.270 --> 00:15:06.820
You know?

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:08.190
But I got somewhere.

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:09.870
I was trying.

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:12.984
And I would wear, like,
t-shirts, shorts, cap.

00:15:12.984 --> 00:15:14.650
And they don't dress
like that in Egypt.

00:15:14.650 --> 00:15:16.640
So I tried to
integrate everything,

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:21.250
and I even learned how
to walk like an Egyptian.

00:15:21.250 --> 00:15:22.830
And it's not this.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:25.219
If you've ever played
the old game "Frogger,"

00:15:25.219 --> 00:15:27.510
where you got to, like, hop
across the road, like this,

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:31.440
and go between the cars, that's
kind of what life in Egypt--

00:15:31.440 --> 00:15:33.150
in Cairo, especially-- is like.

00:15:33.150 --> 00:15:37.775
You have eight lanes of traffic,
never a pedestrian crossing.

00:15:37.775 --> 00:15:39.650
So if you ever want to
walk like an Egyptian,

00:15:39.650 --> 00:15:44.120
just, like, grab your phone,
and just kind of stroll

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:45.800
across like this.

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:47.830
And the cars will
swerve around you.

00:15:47.830 --> 00:15:51.220
And everyone will think
that Egyptian guy,

00:15:51.220 --> 00:15:53.340
he knows what he's doing.

00:15:53.340 --> 00:15:54.790
You know?

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:56.820
And after I did that,
whenever I tried

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:03.190
to find accommodation or
haggle the price of something,

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:04.170
it changed a lot.

00:16:04.170 --> 00:16:06.060
Wasn't just speaking
the language,

00:16:06.060 --> 00:16:08.840
it was speaking the culture.

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.457
And that gets prices
down dramatically.

00:16:11.457 --> 00:16:13.290
So that's kind of
something to keep in mind.

00:16:13.290 --> 00:16:15.380
If you wanted to travel,
you don't actually

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:17.810
have to have wads
of cash for it.

00:16:17.810 --> 00:16:22.920
You just have to try to get to
know how people do it locally.

00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:26.480
But the way you use the wads
of cash does make a difference.

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:28.540
It's all about mentality.

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:32.470
So I do have to
admit, it's true.

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:34.370
I'm a millionaire.

00:16:34.370 --> 00:16:35.650
Let's get that out there.

00:16:35.650 --> 00:16:37.150
This is proof.

00:16:37.150 --> 00:16:42.610
This is me holding one
million Indonesian rupiah,

00:16:42.610 --> 00:16:45.550
which is about 80 euro.

00:16:45.550 --> 00:16:49.400
So the lifestyle you lead makes
you feel like a millionaire

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:55.820
sometimes, even if you're just
an Indonesian millionaire.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:59.390
So I try to see, how
can I hack those things?

00:16:59.390 --> 00:17:03.770
How can I try to get things
that would not necessarily

00:17:03.770 --> 00:17:07.470
be that expensive, but
still feel expensive?

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:11.599
And for that, I would try to
get the right connections.

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:15.270
So I tried to learn to
be more outgoing, which

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:16.089
was hard for me.

00:17:16.089 --> 00:17:18.790
I was a very shy person.

00:17:18.790 --> 00:17:22.270
Growing up, in
university, I just--

00:17:22.270 --> 00:17:27.069
I became the best player of
Snake for the Nokia phone,

00:17:27.069 --> 00:17:29.580
because every time I
go out to socialize,

00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:31.740
I'd, like, pretend like
I'm texting, you know,

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:33.830
my thousands of
friends that I'm, like,

00:17:33.830 --> 00:17:36.910
so busy texting all the
time, when I was just playing

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:39.280
that game on the phone,
because I just-- I

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:40.640
couldn't approach people.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:44.140
I was so scared of
what they would think.

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:48.120
But I found that just letting
go of that a little bit,

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:50.950
and trying to get to
know a lot of people,

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:53.070
has given me a
lot of connections

00:17:53.070 --> 00:17:56.300
to get to do a lot of
things that I always thought

00:17:56.300 --> 00:17:59.170
only millionaires could do.

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:01.840
So whenever people
would ask me, you know,

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:04.710
how can I do that,
if I'm shy, you know?

00:18:04.710 --> 00:18:07.110
And the best example
I can think of that I

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:09.170
was able to change
this for somebody

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:13.130
was while I was learning
German in Berlin,

00:18:13.130 --> 00:18:16.580
one of my methods of
learning the language is

00:18:16.580 --> 00:18:18.960
to speak only in that language.

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:23.810
Sticking to that-- of never
switching to English while I'm

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:27.630
in the several hours time
I'm using the language.

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:31.790
So I met a German lady, and
she wanted to practice English.

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:34.702
And she was introduced to
me by some friends of hers.

00:18:34.702 --> 00:18:36.410
And she never would
have walked up to me,

00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:38.420
because she told me,
the first thing she said

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:39.842
is that she's very shy.

00:18:39.842 --> 00:18:41.300
And she wanted to
practice English,

00:18:41.300 --> 00:18:42.750
but I was in German mode.

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:44.000
So I still wanted to help her.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.320
I wanted to give
her some advice,

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:48.950
and there were some
Americans in the same event,

00:18:48.950 --> 00:18:51.579
so I wanted to make sure
she could talk to them.

00:18:51.579 --> 00:18:53.120
And I said, yeah,
those guys there, I

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:54.244
was talking to them before.

00:18:54.244 --> 00:18:55.250
They're very friendly.

00:18:55.250 --> 00:18:56.680
You should go say hi.

00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:58.810
And she said, I can't do that.

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:00.776
I'm too shy.

00:19:00.776 --> 00:19:03.890
And I didn't want to just,
like, do the work for her.

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:05.844
I wanted to help her
get over this shyness.

00:19:05.844 --> 00:19:07.260
So I tried to think
to myself, how

00:19:07.260 --> 00:19:11.880
can I show this lady how she can
do it, so that when I'm gone,

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:14.740
she'll be able to
approach people and expand

00:19:14.740 --> 00:19:17.510
her social circle to
learn English better?

00:19:17.510 --> 00:19:19.180
And then I had an idea.

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:22.850
So she was holding a glass
of something, some drink.

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:27.120
And I said, do you know how
blood flow to your brain

00:19:27.120 --> 00:19:28.760
makes you smarter?

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:31.790
And she was like, but
that doesn't sound right.

00:19:31.790 --> 00:19:33.350
I was like, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:19:33.350 --> 00:19:33.850
Trust me.

00:19:33.850 --> 00:19:34.600
Trust me.

00:19:34.600 --> 00:19:36.290
And like, if you were
to raise your arm,

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:40.190
for instance, then more blood
goes down, up into your brain,

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:43.050
and you will be smarter.

00:19:43.050 --> 00:19:46.595
And this whole time, like,
she was very, very confused,

00:19:46.595 --> 00:19:48.720
and wondering, you know,
this guy is kind of weird.

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:50.510
What's he talking about?

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:52.430
But what she didn't
know is we were

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:56.060
kind of moving in a
particular direction.

00:19:56.060 --> 00:20:00.450
So I was moving her towards
those two American guys,

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:05.680
and completely distracting her
with this nonsense about blood

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:07.400
and hands and stuff.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:10.070
And then, at the right moment,
when we were close enough,

00:20:10.070 --> 00:20:12.550
and I was moving
her arm up and down,

00:20:12.550 --> 00:20:17.720
I clinked her glass against
theirs, and I ran away.

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:20.500
Then, one hour later,
she came up to me

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:23.710
and she said she had
the best night ever.

00:20:23.710 --> 00:20:25.940
She got to talk to these guys.

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:28.310
She found out they live
in the same neighborhood.

00:20:28.310 --> 00:20:30.580
They're going to be hanging
out all weekend long.

00:20:30.580 --> 00:20:33.670
And she made all of
these connections.

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:39.190
And what she realized was that
the shyness she was feeling

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:42.160
was mostly a lot of
self-fulfilling prophecy.

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:44.880
She was telling herself,
if I go up to them,

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:47.650
they're going to laugh
at me for trying.

00:20:47.650 --> 00:20:50.060
They're going to think
my English is bad.

00:20:50.060 --> 00:20:52.050
They're going to think
my pronunciation is off.

00:20:52.050 --> 00:20:54.910
They're going to think I'm
not an interesting person.

00:20:54.910 --> 00:20:57.580
But what I did is I took
all of that away from her.

00:20:57.580 --> 00:21:02.050
I took the ability to
talk herself out of it.

00:21:02.050 --> 00:21:03.380
I took it away.

00:21:03.380 --> 00:21:07.920
And by just presenting the
moment, she just said hello.

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:09.930
And it went from there.

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:11.590
And that's the kind
of thing that I

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:16.760
do when I want to expand
my network, to expand

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:20.170
my opportunities to have
that different lifestyle.

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:23.030
I see somebody that I
would like to talk to,

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:26.270
and I don't start an
inner dialogue of, OK,

00:21:26.270 --> 00:21:28.935
what's a clever way to start a
conversation with that person?

00:21:28.935 --> 00:21:31.370
No, if I say that, they're
going to think I'm an idiot.

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:33.210
And I wouldn't think that.

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:35.180
I'd just see someone, hello.

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:36.180
So try to think of that.

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:38.780
If you want to, like,
get out of your shell,

00:21:38.780 --> 00:21:42.870
and you want to, you know,
experience different things,

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:45.640
and you see an opportunity,
grab it immediately.

00:21:45.640 --> 00:21:48.950
Do not even think for a second.

00:21:48.950 --> 00:21:53.030
That is going to lead
to so many more things.

00:21:53.030 --> 00:21:54.870
It might lead to
some embarrassment.

00:21:54.870 --> 00:21:56.560
You might make a
couple of mistakes.

00:21:56.560 --> 00:21:59.600
But my whole lifestyle,
especially thanks to language

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:02.100
learning, is I
have a goal to make

00:22:02.100 --> 00:22:05.002
at least 200 mistakes a day.

00:22:05.002 --> 00:22:06.460
And when you go up
to somebody, you

00:22:06.460 --> 00:22:09.480
try to talk to them, most
of the time, it's fine.

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:10.750
Everything works out great.

00:22:10.750 --> 00:22:13.060
And sometimes they
kind of are confused,

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:14.330
why do you talk to them?

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:16.610
Then you just be
like, OK, great.

00:22:16.610 --> 00:22:20.210
That's one of my mistakes
ticked off the list.

00:22:20.210 --> 00:22:22.990
And it helps a lot
when you do that

00:22:22.990 --> 00:22:25.690
with so many aspects of life.

00:22:25.690 --> 00:22:27.770
OK, and then of
course, it helps you

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:30.510
to feel like you get
to live a lot richer.

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:32.350
I've-- the kind of
people I've met,

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:36.640
they've given me these kind
of different opportunities.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:38.350
When I went to
Japan, for instance,

00:22:38.350 --> 00:22:43.500
I tried to build a relationship
with my Airbnb host.

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:45.960
You know, I was
emailing him in advance.

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:49.590
But then we arrived, and the
keys were not left out for me.

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:51.935
And I was tired,
exhausted from jet lag.

00:22:51.935 --> 00:22:54.990
And kind of sitting outside, I
couldn't get in touch with him.

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:56.766
And I was starting
to get frustrated.

00:22:56.766 --> 00:22:59.140
And I kind of knocked on the
neighbor's door, and I said,

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:00.556
is there any chance
you guys would

00:23:00.556 --> 00:23:02.680
have a key to this apartment?

00:23:02.680 --> 00:23:08.220
And it turned out that it's kind
of illegal to do Airbnb hosting

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:09.730
in the building he was at.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:12.110
So the police were called.

00:23:12.110 --> 00:23:15.280
They came in, and they wanted
to take a statement from me.

00:23:15.280 --> 00:23:17.970
And they weren't--
I wasn't in trouble.

00:23:17.970 --> 00:23:20.020
They were trying to
protect-- because they

00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:22.500
were very protective of
the tourism industry.

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:25.610
They didn't want foreigners
to be taken advantage of.

00:23:25.610 --> 00:23:29.550
But they were like, did you
pay him money to stay here?

00:23:29.550 --> 00:23:31.750
And I kind of--
that was the moment

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:33.490
when suddenly I forgot
all the Japanese

00:23:33.490 --> 00:23:34.531
that I had been learning.

00:23:34.531 --> 00:23:35.650
And I was like, what?

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:36.770
Sorry, no.

00:23:36.770 --> 00:23:38.910
I just, like, forgot it all.

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:40.610
I had spoken Japanese
up to that moment,

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:44.370
and somehow it just
disappeared from my head.

00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:47.950
And so I wasn't able to take a
very solid statement with them.

00:23:47.950 --> 00:23:51.010
And I called this guy the
next day, thinking, you know,

00:23:51.010 --> 00:23:54.992
I put myself out there for you.

00:23:54.992 --> 00:23:57.750
You did not give me
this accommodation

00:23:57.750 --> 00:24:00.260
for this tiny little
room that I wanted.

00:24:00.260 --> 00:24:03.990
And he was so appreciative
that I tried to help him,

00:24:03.990 --> 00:24:07.340
he put me up in a
penthouse apartment

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:12.900
with a 270-degree
panoramic view of Kyoto.

00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:15.000
And I was there for
a week and a half.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.550
And that was from paying
the same amount for, like,

00:24:17.550 --> 00:24:22.080
a tiny little shoe box, like,
hidden away in a small street.

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:24.860
So a lot of the time,
I make my travels

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:28.080
about building these
relationships-- trying

00:24:28.080 --> 00:24:31.450
to do people favors,
if I can, and then

00:24:31.450 --> 00:24:33.850
to see how that
comes back to me.

00:24:33.850 --> 00:24:36.020
Another way that
you can make sure

00:24:36.020 --> 00:24:40.710
that it doesn't cost you as much
is to not make it about stuff,

00:24:40.710 --> 00:24:41.860
owning things.

00:24:41.860 --> 00:24:44.620
This, for instance, is
something I used to own.

00:24:44.620 --> 00:24:48.010
