00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:03.437
about travel and working and
language learning and so on--

00:27:03.437 --> 00:27:04.770
is the language learning aspect.

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:08.880
So when I try to learn a
language, I try to see,

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:12.670
how can I learn this
like an engineer?

00:27:12.670 --> 00:27:16.780
And I feel like that has been
the biggest advantage that I've

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.970
had, my engineering background,
in language learning.

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:22.634
Because a lot of
people I've met,

00:27:22.634 --> 00:27:24.050
when they try to
get into learning

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:26.420
a language as an
adult, have too much

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:29.360
of a perfectionist
attitude to it.

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:31.760
They feel like they
can't speak unless they

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:34.520
don't make any mistakes.

00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:36.330
Now, the problem with
that is a language

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:39.060
is a means of communication
between people.

00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:40.949
It's not about being perfect.

00:27:40.949 --> 00:27:42.490
It's about getting
your point across.

00:27:42.490 --> 00:27:45.500
And I always tell people
that the first moment

00:27:45.500 --> 00:27:48.220
I realized I could speak
another language was in Spain.

00:27:48.220 --> 00:27:51.920
When I was just two
weeks into my project

00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:56.090
of trying to speak just Spanish,
my electric toothbrush broke.

00:27:56.090 --> 00:27:57.590
And I was furious.

00:27:57.590 --> 00:28:01.490
I couldn't afford the
10 euro I spent on this.

00:28:01.490 --> 00:28:05.550
So I stormed down to the
supermarket to demand a refund.

00:28:05.550 --> 00:28:09.650
I found the manager,
and I said--

00:28:09.650 --> 00:28:13.710
I don't know how to say
"toothbrush" in Spanish.

00:28:13.710 --> 00:28:15.920
Or "broken."

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:17.650
Or "refund."

00:28:17.650 --> 00:28:21.420
So I didn't actually-- I
wasn't actually able to express

00:28:21.420 --> 00:28:22.330
all those things.

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:24.590
But something happened
in that moment.

00:28:24.590 --> 00:28:28.350
Just the fact that, like I said
before, I wasn't overanalyzing.

00:28:28.350 --> 00:28:30.230
I wasn't thinking
about it too much.

00:28:30.230 --> 00:28:33.360
In that moment, I realized,
I should just do what I can.

00:28:33.360 --> 00:28:35.510
I wanted to achieve this thing.

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:37.030
So I said [SPEAKING SPANISH].

00:28:41.030 --> 00:28:44.000
Tooth machine bad!

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.970
[SPEAKING SPANISH]
Money return trip!

00:28:52.090 --> 00:28:53.260
And you know what?

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:55.260
It worked.

00:28:55.260 --> 00:28:56.550
I got my money back.

00:28:56.550 --> 00:29:00.680
And, like, even with that
abysmal Tarzan Spanish,

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:03.210
I was able to achieve something.

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:07.140
And this is what I've learned
in terms of language hacking,

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:11.340
is that I try to just achieve
the goal of communication.

00:29:11.340 --> 00:29:13.430
And as a beginner,
that's what I try to do.

00:29:13.430 --> 00:29:15.100
Not perfectionism.

00:29:15.100 --> 00:29:17.330
And the reason that this
ties into the engineering

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:19.790
is because from the
first jobs I've had,

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:23.590
we as engineers have
a ship-it mentality.

00:29:23.590 --> 00:29:26.812
If you're making software,
you have a deadline.

00:29:26.812 --> 00:29:28.520
And by the time that
deadline is reached,

00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:32.880
and you wrap up the
code, and it's ready.

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:34.490
And the same with
if you're building

00:29:34.490 --> 00:29:37.350
a device, building
the next Nexus,

00:29:37.350 --> 00:29:39.690
you have to finish it by a date.

00:29:39.690 --> 00:29:42.370
But on that date, you
know there might be still

00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:43.750
things you can improve.

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:46.400
Maybe the latest
chip just came out,

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:48.810
and you could technically
kind of try to put it in.

00:29:48.810 --> 00:29:52.767
Or maybe you didn't realize if
there was a part of the code

00:29:52.767 --> 00:29:55.100
that you could try to analyze
to make sure you could get

00:29:55.100 --> 00:29:58.170
the lines down by just
a couple, you know,

00:29:58.170 --> 00:30:01.390
because it always helps just
the speed ever so slightly.

00:30:01.390 --> 00:30:02.360
But we don't do that.

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:05.330
In engineering,
we try to ship it.

00:30:05.330 --> 00:30:07.610
You just get
something done so it's

00:30:07.610 --> 00:30:11.360
very good, but not perfect.

00:30:11.360 --> 00:30:14.275
We have thermodynamics
and mechanical engineering

00:30:14.275 --> 00:30:15.400
and structural engineering.

00:30:15.400 --> 00:30:16.720
You lose things that way.

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:19.830
Perfectionism can't be the goal.

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:22.340
Mistakes are inevitable.

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:23.910
So just let them happen.

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:25.410
And that's what I
do with languages.

00:30:25.410 --> 00:30:30.060
I try to have a deadline, get
what I can done before then,

00:30:30.060 --> 00:30:32.420
and reach a
particular milestone,

00:30:32.420 --> 00:30:36.180
and be happy with that, rather
than aiming for perfectionism,

00:30:36.180 --> 00:30:39.000
because that's impossible.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.890
There's nobody in this room who
speaks any language perfectly,

00:30:41.890 --> 00:30:45.120
including me and English,
as a native speaker.

00:30:45.120 --> 00:30:49.360
There are always things I'm
learning, always new words.

00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:53.480
Like, I made the dumbest
mistake a few months ago,

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:56.020
when my partner and
I were hanging out,

00:30:56.020 --> 00:30:59.700
and I said something
like, I love you, hubby.

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:03.020
And she said, do you know
what that word means?

00:31:03.020 --> 00:31:05.690
And I was like, yeah, yeah,
it's a term of endearment.

00:31:05.690 --> 00:31:08.000
And she said, yeah, for husband.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.610
You just called me your husband.

00:31:09.610 --> 00:31:11.940
And I was like, oh, OK.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:14.080
So I'm still learning English.

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:16.820
So if you keep that in
mind, you will never

00:31:16.820 --> 00:31:19.400
reach a stage of
perfectionism, but maybe you

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:22.030
can reach those milestones.

00:31:22.030 --> 00:31:25.540
And this, for me, is what I've
taken away from my engineering,

00:31:25.540 --> 00:31:27.620
especially, as I
apply it to languages.

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:29.780
I try to have a
systematic approach,

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:33.120
try to get the best
shortcuts, reach a goal,

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:38.420
and then start a new project,
for the language 2.0.

00:31:38.420 --> 00:31:41.170
So that's a little bit of
what I wanted to talk about.

