I've found to have

00:37:00.334 --> 00:37:02.000
a solid enough level
that you don't even

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:03.220
need to worry about that.

00:37:03.220 --> 00:37:05.230
Like, you can still take
a break of a few months

00:37:05.230 --> 00:37:07.790
and be able to switch
back into speaking it,

00:37:07.790 --> 00:37:11.200
is to focus on
learning one language

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:13.690
till you get it to
a very good level.

00:37:13.690 --> 00:37:15.790
Because I've never
had success in trying

00:37:15.790 --> 00:37:19.280
to learn multiple languages at
the same time at low levels.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:22.740
So my whole process has been,
like, a three-month project

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:25.480
where I am intensively
studying this language

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:27.160
to see how high I can get it.

00:37:27.160 --> 00:37:30.490
If I'm lucky, I'll get it to,
like, a lower intermediate,

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:33.370
or B1 as they call them on
the European common framework,

00:37:33.370 --> 00:37:36.260
or sometimes even a B2.

00:37:36.260 --> 00:37:38.640
I wouldn't aim for the higher
ones in a shorter time,

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:41.300
but I'd get to that stage
where I'm effectively

00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:45.250
fluent in social situations.

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:46.850
But when I get to
that stage, I feel

00:37:46.850 --> 00:37:50.840
like I've built a very strong
wall around the language

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:54.780
in my mind, so it's less
likely to kind of leak

00:37:54.780 --> 00:37:56.610
into the other languages.

00:37:56.610 --> 00:37:59.110
So my whole process is
learn each language up

00:37:59.110 --> 00:38:03.050
to that B2, like,
solid level, and then

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:04.300
maybe start the next language.

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:06.330
And it's OK if I take a break.

00:38:06.330 --> 00:38:09.330
Because having a bunch of
languages at a lower level,

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:11.370
it's very, very hard
to distinguish them.

00:38:11.370 --> 00:38:13.240
They're going to
influence each other.

00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:15.970
But if you can build that
wall, that's a lot better.

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:16.490
Yeah.

00:38:16.490 --> 00:38:19.199
And if you want to jump
in with your question.

00:38:19.199 --> 00:38:20.032
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:20.032 --> 00:38:23.294
I just wanted to
know whether you

00:38:23.294 --> 00:38:25.630
think that this "fluent
in three months"

00:38:25.630 --> 00:38:29.205
process would work in
the same way [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:29.205 --> 00:38:30.205
BENNY LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:38:30.205 --> 00:38:31.540
Whoops.

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:35.520
So firstly, my whole
philosophy, like, the blog,

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:40.080
"Fluent In Three Months,"
that's based off specificity,

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:41.580
because I found
when I first started

00:38:41.580 --> 00:38:44.960
to try to learn Spanish,
didn't have any end goals.

00:38:44.960 --> 00:38:47.140
I just wanted to learn Spanish.

00:38:47.140 --> 00:38:49.660
And my blog, as you can
imagine, gets a big spike

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:52.914
in traffic on January
1, from everyone saying,

00:38:52.914 --> 00:38:53.830
New Year's resolution!

00:38:53.830 --> 00:38:55.410
I want to learn Italian.

00:38:55.410 --> 00:38:57.400
And I don't think
that's a very good idea.

00:38:57.400 --> 00:38:58.900
I think the specifics
[INAUDIBLE].

00:38:58.900 --> 00:39:00.960
So maybe people get
to know those levels,

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:03.330
and maybe they want
to aim for a B1 or B2,

00:39:03.330 --> 00:39:05.530
in three months or six
months or whatever.

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:08.040
So that's, like, what
my strategy would be.

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:10.900
Before, the whole
process for me,

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:14.590
to get to at least basic
conversation level,

00:39:14.590 --> 00:39:17.430
is speak from day one.

00:39:17.430 --> 00:39:19.260
And only speak.

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:22.310
The whole reading and
writing and, like,

00:39:22.310 --> 00:39:26.420
tidying up your grammar, that I
think is-- for a lot of people,

00:39:26.420 --> 00:39:29.610
it's not useful as a beginner.

00:39:29.610 --> 00:39:31.720
It is useful later.

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:34.505
So you can reach the stage
where your conversation

00:39:34.505 --> 00:39:38.480
in the language without having
to worry about reading it.

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:41.940
And in fact, some methods
that I've found online

00:39:41.940 --> 00:39:45.020
intentionally get
people to not read,

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:46.810
because you have a
big advantage there

00:39:46.810 --> 00:39:50.020
of not getting influenced
by English spelling.

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:52.200
So if anything, you
should take that

00:39:52.200 --> 00:39:55.084
as seeing what kind of
strengths would that give you,

00:39:55.084 --> 00:39:56.500
because you can
avoid all of that.

00:39:56.500 --> 00:40:00.979
There are loads of listening
to's, and if you just focus

00:40:00.979 --> 00:40:02.520
on the sounds of
the language, rather

00:40:02.520 --> 00:40:05.040
than trying to associate
spelling and so on,

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:07.887
you don't have to learn how
to read and write initially.

00:40:07.887 --> 00:40:09.220
You might want to do that later.

00:40:09.220 --> 00:40:11.261
And then maybe later you'll
decide you don't even

00:40:11.261 --> 00:40:13.480
want to, if the only
thing you care about

00:40:13.480 --> 00:40:15.440
is speaking the language.

00:40:15.440 --> 00:40:17.280
So I always try to see that.

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:20.620
And I would only try to,
like, improve my reading

00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:22.740
and writing much later on.

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:25.160
So you might want to
decide, you don't even

00:40:25.160 --> 00:40:28.370
want to do that in a language.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:30.520
OK?

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:32.590
And back here?

00:40:32.590 --> 00:40:33.795
OK.

00:40:33.795 --> 00:40:36.282
AUDIENCE: How do you
handle comprehension?

00:40:36.282 --> 00:40:36.990
BENNY LEWIS: Yes.

00:40:36.990 --> 00:40:39.060
Very good question,
because when you're

00:40:39.060 --> 00:40:40.660
speaking to somebody
in a language,

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:43.110
then they might
speak back to you.

00:40:43.110 --> 00:40:47.195
And you will hear
blah blah blah.

00:40:47.195 --> 00:40:49.930
So I think, again,
the perfectionist way

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:55.286
of looking at that is, that
was a large bunch of noise

00:40:55.286 --> 00:40:56.970
that I don't understand.

00:40:56.970 --> 00:40:59.070
So I give up.

00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:01.350
But what I try to do
is a couple of things.

00:41:01.350 --> 00:41:03.850
Like, once, for
instance, the TEDx

00:41:03.850 --> 00:41:05.950
picture I showed up,
that was in Warsaw.

00:41:05.950 --> 00:41:10.010
And I gave myself, like,
just a couple of hours,

00:41:10.010 --> 00:41:13.820
like literally an hour and
a half, to learn Polish.

00:41:13.820 --> 00:41:15.675
And after that, I got on Skype.

00:41:15.675 --> 00:41:17.550
And I was like, I'm
going to Skype in Polish.

00:41:17.550 --> 00:41:20.470
I'm going to not
speak any English.

00:41:20.470 --> 00:41:24.050
And of course, pretty
much everything

00:41:24.050 --> 00:41:28.290
that was said back to
me was gobbledygook.

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:31.330
So I still managed to
have a conversation.

00:41:31.330 --> 00:41:35.260
I hacked that conversation,
because if you're doing it on,

00:41:35.260 --> 00:41:39.350
like, an online voice call,
then you just text them.

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:41.280
Or, like, text-type them.

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:45.210
So what I would do is, I would
look up what I wanted to say,

00:41:45.210 --> 00:41:48.230
and, like, Tarzan
connect it all up.

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:50.760
I'm sure it was, like,
a horrible sentence.

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:53.090
But I would say something
like the equivalent of,

00:41:53.090 --> 00:41:55.560
me Benny, me Ireland.

00:41:55.560 --> 00:41:57.146
And they'd say, blah blah blah.

00:41:57.146 --> 00:41:57.770
And I'd be, OK.

00:41:57.770 --> 00:41:58.270
OK.

00:41:58.270 --> 00:42:01.190
And I type, I'm sorry,
could you type that?

00:42:01.190 --> 00:42:02.190
And then they'd type it.

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:04.860
And I would copy and paste
it into Google Translate,

00:42:04.860 --> 00:42:07.560
see what the-- effectively
what they're saying,

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:08.480
and then be like, OK.

00:42:08.480 --> 00:42:08.890
All right.

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:11.306
And then I would, like, try
to come up with my reply using

00:42:11.306 --> 00:42:12.400
some dictionaries.

00:42:12.400 --> 00:42:14.330
And so I kind of
cheated that way.

00:42:14.330 --> 00:42:16.370
And that got me the
initial momentum.

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:17.970
So that's one way
to do it online.

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:23.140
But then in person, you have
to let go of the perfectionism.

00:42:23.140 --> 00:42:29.430
So instead, I would think of
it as a guesstimation process.

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:32.220
So I wrote my
undergraduate thesis

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:35.160
in Trellis code modulation.

00:42:35.160 --> 00:42:41.200
This is a style of encoding we
have in telephone calls that

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:45.020
decides that some information
is going to be lost,

00:42:45.020 --> 00:42:47.230
because no system is perfect.

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:49.784
So I imagine language learning
to be a little bit like that.

00:42:49.784 --> 00:42:50.450
So imagine this.

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:52.730
Imagine you are having
a telephone call

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:55.350
with somebody in
English, and it was

00:42:55.350 --> 00:42:57.610
very-- it was a very bad line.

00:42:57.610 --> 00:43:00.730
And all you heard was
[WHOOSHING NOISE] dinner

00:43:00.730 --> 00:43:03.720
[WHOOSH] Friday [WHOOSH].

00:43:03.720 --> 00:43:08.410
So you could decide, didn't
understand that at all.

00:43:08.410 --> 00:43:09.766
Like, pointless.

00:43:09.766 --> 00:43:12.140
You'll just have to tell them
to start over, or say look,

00:43:12.140 --> 00:43:13.430
we'll just text each other.

00:43:13.430 --> 00:43:14.971
But there's another
thing you can do.

00:43:14.971 --> 00:43:16.020
You can guess.

00:43:16.020 --> 00:43:20.410
You know, it's probable that
they're saying something like,

00:43:20.410 --> 00:43:23.500
would you like to go out
for dinner on Friday?

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:24.890
It's likely.

00:43:24.890 --> 00:43:27.000
It's less likely that
they're going to say,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.960
the alien invasion
begins on Friday,

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:33.065
and you are going
to be their dinner.

00:43:33.065 --> 00:43:33.720
You know?

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:36.257
So you think to yourself,
in terms of probability,

00:43:36.257 --> 00:43:37.590
it's likely they're saying that.

00:43:37.590 --> 00:43:39.440
So when I'm learning
another language,

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:43.760
I'll hear this stream of noise,
that there's no possible way I

00:43:43.760 --> 00:43:46.440
can give a good translation of.

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:50.730
But maybe there's one
word that I try to catch.

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:53.120
So I never think to
myself-- as they're

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:55.120
speaking, I'm not thinking,
how can I understand

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:57.240
this entire sentence?

00:43:57.240 --> 00:44:01.790
I'm thinking, can I catch
a single word out of that?

00:44:01.790 --> 00:44:04.450
And maybe they will
say the single word

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:06.350
that I happen to understand.

00:44:06.350 --> 00:44:08.830
And if I don't, then
I'll try to say,

00:44:08.830 --> 00:44:12.360
could you say that again,
using different words, please?

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:14.780
And they may in fact
actually say the word

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:17.170
that I need to guess.

00:44:17.170 --> 00:44:19.670
And sometimes, when you
guess, you'll guess wrong.

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:22.770
And the earth has never opened
up and swallowed me whole

00:44:22.770 --> 00:44:24.340
when that happens.

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:26.650
I just-- they see
I'm misunderstanding

00:44:26.650 --> 00:44:28.390
and we work around it.

00:44:28.390 --> 00:44:31.030
So in terms of comprehension,
you could do that.

00:44:31.030 --> 00:44:32.690
And then final
little trick I'd say

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:39.161
is I would listen to
slowly spoken-out language.

00:44:39.161 --> 00:44:42.110
And there's, like, a
lot of online podcast

00:44:42.110 --> 00:44:43.690
series that do this very well.

00:44:43.690 --> 00:44:47.720
So what they do is they start
by giving a 15-second exchange,

00:44:47.720 --> 00:44:50.160
like maybe just buying
something and saying, that costs

00:44:50.160 --> 00:44:51.700
that much, thank you.

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:54.160
And they spend 15
minutes explaining that,

00:44:54.160 --> 00:44:56.190
explaining each word.

00:44:56.190 --> 00:44:58.650
And you start with that, and
then you push yourself up.

00:44:58.650 --> 00:45:01.910
And they're like-- they actually
follow the European framework.

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:03.990
And you get to the A2
level, and maybe they

00:45:03.990 --> 00:45:06.020
have a 30-second
exchange, and they only

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:08.060
explain the hardest parts.

00:45:08.060 --> 00:45:12.950
So pushing yourself up
in notches helps a lot.

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:17.140
When I first moved to Spain,
and they spoke this machine gun

00:45:17.140 --> 00:45:21.300
Spanish at me, it was
impossible for me to understand.

00:45:21.300 --> 00:45:26.260
But I found that if I had these
kind of slower conversations,

00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:29.150
I started to speak with
other learners, not just

00:45:29.150 --> 00:45:30.160
native speakers.

00:45:30.160 --> 00:45:33.050
I learned most of my Spanish
from Erasmus students,

00:45:33.050 --> 00:45:36.030
from French and German and
Italian students, because they

00:45:36.030 --> 00:45:37.840
would speak slowly to me.

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:40.540
And that didn't mean I
was going to speak slowly

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:41.720
for the rest of my life.

00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:45.580
It meant I got that initial
momentum to work my way up,

00:45:45.580 --> 00:45:48.070
to eventually be able
to have more confident,

00:45:48.070 --> 00:45:49.760
fast conversations.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:53.021
So a few different
suggestions for you there.

00:45:53.021 --> 00:45:53.521
OK?

00:45:57.818 --> 00:45:58.526
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:45:58.526 --> 00:46:02.650
You probably have been to
many interesting situations

00:46:02.650 --> 00:46:04.130
during your world travel.

00:46:04.130 --> 00:46:06.210
If you can share, how
have your Jason Bourne

00:46:06.210 --> 00:46:08.130
and your culture
or language skills

00:46:08.130 --> 00:46:12.804
helped you to get out of
some of the tricky ones?

00:46:12.804 --> 00:46:13.470
BENNY LEWIS: OK.

00:46:13.470 --> 00:46:13.990
All right.

00:46:13.990 --> 00:46:16.680
I'd say the trickiest
situation I had was

00:46:16.680 --> 00:46:21.410
in Brazil, where
I-- essentially, I

00:46:21.410 --> 00:46:25.340
got detained by
the federal police.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:27.700
What happened was I had been
in Brazil for three months,

00:46:27.700 --> 00:46:30.110
and I was having
the best time ever.

00:46:30.110 --> 00:46:31.590
And I wanted to stay longer.

00:46:31.590 --> 00:46:34.260
And you don't have
to do a visa run.

00:46:34.260 --> 00:46:36.780
If you're a tourist, you could
just go to the federal police

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:38.990
and ask them if you
can stay longer.

00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:41.220
And they stamp your
passport and that's it.

00:46:41.220 --> 00:46:43.760
And I decided I
wanted to do that.

00:46:43.760 --> 00:46:48.800
I went in, and of course, I
had to queue for five hours.

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:50.640
Very slow bureaucratic process.

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:53.650
I finally got to my turn,
and she said, where's

00:46:53.650 --> 00:46:56.190
your 20 [INAUDIBLE] payment?

00:46:56.190 --> 00:46:57.440
And I was like, here.

00:46:57.440 --> 00:46:57.940
Here you go.

00:46:57.940 --> 00:46:59.023
And she's like no, no, no.

00:46:59.023 --> 00:47:01.550
You've got to go to the bank,
pay them, and then give us

00:47:01.550 --> 00:47:02.060
the receipt.

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:03.120
So I did that.

00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:06.070
I came back, and I had
to start over again.

00:47:06.070 --> 00:47:09.600
So by the time it was my
turn, I was so frustrated

00:47:09.600 --> 00:47:11.180
that I was in a very bad mood.

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:12.710
I was angry.

00:47:12.710 --> 00:47:14.489
And I was like, I'm back.

00:47:14.489 --> 00:47:15.280
Here's the payment.

00:47:15.280 --> 00:47:17.210
Stamp my passport, please.

00:47:17.210 --> 00:47:19.477
And she was like, in
Portuguese, she's saying,

00:47:19.477 --> 00:47:20.810
you can't speak to me like that.

00:47:20.810 --> 00:47:22.740
I'm a federal police officer.

00:47:22.740 --> 00:47:25.660
And I was like,
ugh, I'm so sorry.

00:47:25.660 --> 00:47:26.290
Here.

00:47:26.290 --> 00:47:27.660
Please, pretty please.

00:47:27.660 --> 00:47:30.670
She said, OK, if you're
going to be like that--

00:47:30.670 --> 00:47:34.652
and she stamped my passport
for one day, which meant

00:47:34.652 --> 00:47:35.860
there was nothing I could do.

00:47:35.860 --> 00:47:38.240
I couldn't go to another
place to get it extended.

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:40.430
I was furious.

00:47:40.430 --> 00:47:41.920
I had so many
things outlined, you

00:47:41.920 --> 00:47:43.890
know, things I had
paid for in advance,

00:47:43.890 --> 00:47:45.910
and, like, flights
and everything.

00:47:45.910 --> 00:47:49.100
So mad that I went
out into the queue,

00:47:49.100 --> 00:47:53.420
and I was, like, cursing
all of my worst Portuguese,

00:47:53.420 --> 00:47:57.430
saying this you-know-what has
a stick up her you-know-what

00:47:57.430 --> 00:47:58.740
and she's blah blah blah.

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:01.070
And so, like, I said
horrible, horrible things.

00:48:01.070 --> 00:48:03.390
And I didn't realize
that the window was open

00:48:03.390 --> 00:48:04.720
and she heard everything.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:07.610
So she came out, grabbed
me, threw me in a room,

00:48:07.610 --> 00:48:08.980
and locked me there.

00:48:08.980 --> 00:48:14.550
And she said, we're going
to officially arrest you.

00:48:14.550 --> 00:48:18.330
Now, being arrested was
not on my itinerary.

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:21.920
That was going to mess up
my travel plans very much.

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:23.370
So I had to think quickly.

00:48:23.370 --> 00:48:26.760
I had to think, OK, what
would Jason Bourne do?

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:29.360
Or what would MacGyver do
in this situation to escape?

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:30.735
You know, is there,
like, a paper

00:48:30.735 --> 00:48:32.450
clip I can use to get
out of this place?

00:48:32.450 --> 00:48:34.283
And then I was thinking,
thinking, thinking.

00:48:34.283 --> 00:48:36.110
And then I realized
what I had to do.

00:48:36.110 --> 00:48:39.900
I had a plan, through what
I had learned those three

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:43.720
months in trying to
understand Brazilian culture.

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:47.670
And instead of herself, I
knew that another police

00:48:47.670 --> 00:48:51.460
officer, a guy, he was going
to come in, and he looked mad.

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:55.650
He looked like he was
probably her brother,

00:48:55.650 --> 00:48:57.440
and he had heard what I said.

00:48:57.440 --> 00:49:00.350
So he was ready to give me hell.

00:49:00.350 --> 00:49:02.760
But while he was kind of,
like, leaving the papers

00:49:02.760 --> 00:49:04.990
and coming back, I
thought to myself, OK.

00:49:04.990 --> 00:49:07.170
I concentrated
really, really hard

00:49:07.170 --> 00:49:12.120
on Torlinus, the pet turtle I
had when I was six years old,

00:49:12.120 --> 00:49:13.710
who died.

00:49:13.710 --> 00:49:16.552
And I thought really hard, and
I was, like, poor Torlinus,

00:49:16.552 --> 00:49:17.600
I remember burying him.

00:49:17.600 --> 00:49:19.820
And, like, the tears
started coming down.

00:49:19.820 --> 00:49:26.169
So he came back in, and he was
like, you arrogant foreigners,

00:49:26.169 --> 00:49:27.460
you don't know what's going on.

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:30.900
And I was, I'm so sorry.

00:49:30.900 --> 00:49:33.290
And I bawled in tears.

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:36.520
And the reason I did that is
because I realized this macho

00:49:36.520 --> 00:49:41.460
culture didn't really know
how to handle men crying.

00:49:41.460 --> 00:49:43.110
And he started
getting very awkward.

00:49:43.110 --> 00:49:45.615
And he was like, uh,
stop crying this instant.

00:49:45.615 --> 00:49:46.740
We need to talk about this.

00:49:46.740 --> 00:49:49.390
And I'm like, [CRYING].

00:49:49.390 --> 00:49:51.890
I want my mommy.

00:49:51.890 --> 00:49:55.007
And I kept replying that
way, and eventually,

00:49:55.007 --> 00:49:56.590
since he didn't know
how to handle it,

00:49:56.590 --> 00:49:58.440
he grabbed my passport,
threw it at me,

00:49:58.440 --> 00:49:59.689
and said, get out of my sight!

00:49:59.689 --> 00:50:01.200
You're pathetic!

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:04.420
And I escaped from
prison, as it were,

00:50:04.420 --> 00:50:08.400
using a little bit of that
kind of cultural understanding.

00:50:08.400 --> 00:50:12.260
So sometimes, you know, I got
myself into bad situations.

00:50:12.260 --> 00:50:14.628
But sometimes I can
get myself out of them.

00:50:14.628 --> 00:50:15.128
Yeah.

00:50:21.932 --> 00:50:26.074
AUDIENCE: So I was studying
Chinese for around two years,

00:50:26.074 --> 00:50:28.544
studying on my own,
and [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:28.544 --> 00:50:31.014
I had my first
conversation with somebody,

00:50:31.014 --> 00:50:34.966
I realized I didn't know
the word-- the sentence for

00:50:34.966 --> 00:50:38.424
"Can you repeat again?" or
"Please [INAUDIBLE] slower."

00:50:38.424 --> 00:50:41.882
Do you have a list of basic
sentences that help you, like,

00:50:41.882 --> 00:50:44.846
[INAUDIBLE] a language,
as in, you know,

00:50:44.846 --> 00:50:46.360
these kinds of words that--

00:50:46.360 --> 00:50:47.287
BENNY LEWIS: Yeah.

00:50:47.287 --> 00:50:48.082
AUDIENCE: --that
you find that you

00:50:48.082 --> 00:50:50.150
need to use more often than not
when you start a new language?

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:50.760
BENNY LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:50:50.760 --> 00:50:51.140
No, no, no.

00:50:51.140 --> 00:50:52.306
I always try to learn those.

00:50:52.306 --> 00:50:54.250
But instead of
saying, I'm sorry,

00:50:54.250 --> 00:50:55.840
can you repeat that again?

00:50:55.840 --> 00:50:57.750
I just learn the word "again."

00:50:57.750 --> 00:50:58.500
It's a lot easier.

00:50:58.500 --> 00:50:59.890
It's a lot less complicated.

00:50:59.890 --> 00:51:01.730
It's a lot less intimidating.

00:51:01.730 --> 00:51:05.440
So I would say,
[SPEAKING CHINESE], again.

00:51:05.440 --> 00:51:07.200
And then they know.

00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:08.930
And then maybe
after a month or so,

00:51:08.930 --> 00:51:12.970
I'll actually give a more
proper way of saying that.

00:51:12.970 --> 00:51:14.570
But I would learn single words.

00:51:14.570 --> 00:51:17.960
What single word can get you
the best bang for your buck?

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:20.530
I always think Pareto
principle-wise,

00:51:20.530 --> 00:51:24.990
what 20% can give me
80% of the results?

00:51:24.990 --> 00:51:26.600
And I'm not trying
to get it perfect.

00:51:26.600 --> 00:51:29.357
I just want to
achieve something.

00:51:29.357 --> 00:51:31.440
And then another thing,
with Mandarin especially--

00:51:31.440 --> 00:51:34.335
people always forget this-- with
any language that you learn,

00:51:34.335 --> 00:51:36.870
and something that I
tried to really dive

00:51:36.870 --> 00:51:39.640
into in these
courses, was to get

00:51:39.640 --> 00:51:43.180
people to see all the
words they already know.

00:51:43.180 --> 00:51:45.630
And this is very prominent
in European languages.

00:51:45.630 --> 00:51:47.980
We have a lot of loan
words people use.

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:50.100
But in Mandarin, I
tried to see, what

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:52.035
are the words I already know?

00:51:52.035 --> 00:51:55.100
And there are words
you know already.

00:51:55.100 --> 00:51:56.010
There are loan words.

00:51:56.010 --> 00:51:57.426
There are some
words that are kind

00:51:57.426 --> 00:52:01.560
of building up and getting used
in kind of slang situations.

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:05.498
So like on phone calls,
you could say, bye-bye.

00:52:05.498 --> 00:52:05.998
You know?

00:52:05.998 --> 00:52:08.220
When people would ask
me where I'm from,

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:10.790
I would say "Ireland."

00:52:10.790 --> 00:52:15.360
And you have, like, not just
country names, but brand names.

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:18.315
And you have people's
names, like, if you

00:52:18.315 --> 00:52:20.460
don't know how to say
the word for "president,"

00:52:20.460 --> 00:52:22.690
then use the word for
Obama, because that's

00:52:22.690 --> 00:52:24.070
going to be the same.

00:52:24.070 --> 00:52:26.910
So I would try to think along
those lines, because then

00:52:26.910 --> 00:52:29.130
that is the thing
I would do before I

00:52:29.130 --> 00:52:31.380
need to memorize things.

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:33.300
And then with
memorizing them, I would

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:36.650
try to come up with
quirky mnemonics.

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:38.670
I try to see, is
there some way I

00:52:38.670 --> 00:52:43.050
could tie in the vocabulary
with something else that I know?

00:52:43.050 --> 00:52:45.650
And that helps to just,
like, have something

00:52:45.650 --> 00:52:48.780
ready to spit out, because the
last thing you want to be doing

00:52:48.780 --> 00:52:53.460
is to overthink it when
the situation comes up.

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:56.100
But yeah, for
generally, what I do

00:52:56.100 --> 00:52:57.960
when I'm starting
to learn a language,

00:52:57.960 --> 00:53:01.020
is come up with things
I'm likely to say often.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:02.760
So I do not try
to learn the word

00:53:02.760 --> 00:53:06.020
for "curtain," because that's
very unlikely to come up

00:53:06.020 --> 00:53:06.950
in conversation.

00:53:06.950 --> 00:53:09.730
But on a call,
like a video call,

00:53:09.730 --> 00:53:13.460
I'm going to very likely need
to say, "Repeat, please,"

00:53:13.460 --> 00:53:14.950
and "Can you write?"

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:17.430
"Can you write?" is a very
good one, or "Can you type?"

00:53:17.430 --> 00:53:20.250
because then they're going to
have something you can actually

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:22.020
go off and use very quickly.

00:53:22.020 --> 00:53:24.210
And I don't feel bad
about having them wait.

00:53:24.210 --> 00:53:26.160
If I'm, like, paying
for the lesson,

00:53:26.160 --> 00:53:27.910
then they're just
going to have to wait.

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:28.410
You know?

00:53:28.410 --> 00:53:30.034
And I go off and look
it up, and then I

00:53:30.034 --> 00:53:31.797
continue the conversation.

00:53:31.797 --> 00:53:33.630
So yeah, I would try
to come up with things.

00:53:33.630 --> 00:53:35.320
I do have a baseline list.

00:53:35.320 --> 00:53:37.300
But a lot of the stuff
I come up with initially

00:53:37.300 --> 00:53:39.610
isn't necessarily something
I say, OK, everyone.

00:53:39.610 --> 00:53:41.470
Here are the magic words I use.

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:43.930
Here they go for you,
because in every language,

00:53:43.930 --> 00:53:46.670
I've never ever come across
a course that teaches me

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:51.180
how to say, "I'm Benny,
a blogger from Ireland."

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:54.330
So I-- when I'm, like, making--
when I made this course,

00:53:54.330 --> 00:53:56.620
I tried to make it a
more me-specific thing,

00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:59.330
to give people the
tools they needed

00:53:59.330 --> 00:54:01.280
to figure out how to
fill in those gaps

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:03.260
with something relevant to them.

00:54:03.260 --> 00:54:04.760
OK?

00:54:04.760 --> 00:54:06.510
MODERATOR: OK, I
think we've got time

00:54:06.510 --> 00:54:09.727
for one more quick question.

00:54:09.727 --> 00:54:11.810
AUDIENCE: Thank you very
much for the information.

00:54:11.810 --> 00:54:13.340
It's really useful.

00:54:13.340 --> 00:54:15.994
So I'm Austrian, and
as foreign languages,

00:54:15.994 --> 00:54:19.380
I have some, like, for example,
Italian, French, and Spanish.

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:21.775
And to me it was always really
difficult to mix those up,

00:54:21.775 --> 00:54:24.191
because you have all those
words which are really similar.

00:54:24.191 --> 00:54:27.750
So my question is, would
you say it's easier

00:54:27.750 --> 00:54:30.795
if I learn a language
really well, to start off

00:54:30.795 --> 00:54:32.804
with another language
that's really similar,

00:54:32.804 --> 00:54:34.220
like going from
French to Spanish,

00:54:34.220 --> 00:54:36.386
or would you say, like, do
something completely else

00:54:36.386 --> 00:54:39.874
afterwards, so the brain can
not do something similar?

00:54:39.874 --> 00:54:41.540
BENNY LEWIS: I would
say, like, whenever

00:54:41.540 --> 00:54:43.810
people say, which language
should I learn next?

00:54:43.810 --> 00:54:45.830
And they say, should
it be based on similar?

00:54:45.830 --> 00:54:49.430
Or should it be based on
what's harder, what's easier?

00:54:49.430 --> 00:54:53.130
I always think of this
guy I met in Spain while I

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:57.630
was learning Spanish, and he had
to learn French and Japanese.

00:54:57.630 --> 00:55:01.615
And he was doing a lot
better with Japanese,

00:55:01.615 --> 00:55:02.990
and I was confused.

00:55:02.990 --> 00:55:06.120
I was, like, well, wouldn't
French be easier for you?

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:09.280
And he said, no,
because I love anime,

00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:12.850
and I, like, can't wait for
the next manga to come out,

00:55:12.850 --> 00:55:15.470
and I find Japanese girls hot.

00:55:15.470 --> 00:55:17.450
And, like, that
was his motivation.

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:20.080
And I find, whenever you
start a new language,

00:55:20.080 --> 00:55:22.164
if you start thinking
of, you know,

00:55:22.164 --> 00:55:23.580
will I learn this
language better,

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:27.090
because, you know, it
has vowel agreements,

00:55:27.090 --> 00:55:29.810
and because some of
the words are formed

00:55:29.810 --> 00:55:33.270
in an agglutinative
way, or because of this,

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:35.060
or it's in the same
language family,

00:55:35.060 --> 00:55:37.690
that's a very impersonal
way of looking at it.

00:55:37.690 --> 00:55:40.710
That might make
sense, you'd think,

00:55:40.710 --> 00:55:42.000
from a logical perspective.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.260
But I've found the next
language you should learn

00:55:44.260 --> 00:55:47.310
should be the language
you're most passionate about.

00:55:47.310 --> 00:55:49.430
And that should be
what's driving you,

00:55:49.430 --> 00:55:52.880
regardless of if it's similar,
because if it's similar,

00:55:52.880 --> 00:55:54.440
you'll find a way.

00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:56.560
Maybe technically,
it will be, like,

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:59.270
5% harder because it's similar.

00:55:59.270 --> 00:56:05.142
But maybe it'll be 20% easier
because you care about it more.

00:56:05.142 --> 00:56:06.100
So all of those things.

00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:08.220
The same when people ask
me, what's the hardest

00:56:08.220 --> 00:56:09.600
language you've ever learned?

00:56:09.600 --> 00:56:12.650
I always tell them it
was kind of Spanish.

00:56:12.650 --> 00:56:17.050
It wasn't Chinese or
Hungarian or Quechua.

00:56:17.050 --> 00:56:19.830
It was Spanish,
because I didn't really

00:56:19.830 --> 00:56:21.590
care about it for
the first six months

00:56:21.590 --> 00:56:23.040
that I was trying to learn.

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:25.490
I was just kind of
putting in the work.

00:56:25.490 --> 00:56:29.750
And I put in a lot of hours
to get nothing out of it.

00:56:29.750 --> 00:56:32.740
So, but since then, I've
cared about the culture.

00:56:32.740 --> 00:56:34.310
I've seen a language--
like, people

00:56:34.310 --> 00:56:35.810
are surprised when
I tell them this.

00:56:35.810 --> 00:56:39.250
I actually don't care
about language learning.

00:56:39.250 --> 00:56:41.690
I care about talking to people.

00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:44.660
For me, a language
is a means to an end.

00:56:44.660 --> 00:56:48.520
It's my tool that
lets me open doors.

00:56:48.520 --> 00:56:50.280
That lets me get
through it quicker.

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:53.970
So I don't care if it's
similar to this language,

00:56:53.970 --> 00:56:56.260
or if it's in a different
language family,

00:56:56.260 --> 00:56:58.860
or anything like that,
or does it have tones,

00:56:58.860 --> 00:57:01.420
or does it have seven cases?

00:57:01.420 --> 00:57:03.900
I don't care, because
regardless, I'll

00:57:03.900 --> 00:57:07.740
find a way to figure out
those issues if they come up.

00:57:07.740 --> 00:57:11.450
What matters is, do I want
to learn that language?

00:57:11.450 --> 00:57:12.850
So I would try to see that.

00:57:12.850 --> 00:57:14.150
I would try to see,
is there some part

00:57:14.150 --> 00:57:15.524
of the culture,
is there somebody

00:57:15.524 --> 00:57:17.030
you know you really
want to talk to,

00:57:17.030 --> 00:57:18.900
would you like to
visit the country soon?

00:57:18.900 --> 00:57:21.530
Whatever it is, focus
on that, if you're

00:57:21.530 --> 00:57:22.660
comparing two languages.

00:57:22.660 --> 00:57:25.310
And say, which one comes
out on top as the one

00:57:25.310 --> 00:57:27.240
you want to learn more?

00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:28.650
OK?

00:57:28.650 --> 00:57:29.610
So that's it.

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:31.360
Thank you very much
for coming, everybody.

00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:32.910
[APPLAUSE]

